<h2>More calorie boosting ideas</h2>
<p>Taking this pamphlet with you to the grocery store may be helpful. Make a note of the food items listed that you would like to try and buy them on your next shopping trip. </p>
<h2>Energy boosting ideas for meats and meat alternatives</h2>
<h3>Meat, poultry, fish and tofu</h3>
<ul>
<li>Make sandwiches with two slices of meat and cheese and lots of spreads on both pieces of bread. </li>
<li>Add small pieces of any cooked meat, chicken, fish or tofu to meals. Strained or ground meat works well for younger children. </li>
<li>Wrap cooked and cut-up meat or meat substitute in pie crusts or biscuit dough. Then bake to make pie or turnovers. </li>
</ul>
<h3>Eggs</h3>
<p>Add a raw scrambled egg to soup while the soup is cooking. The soup will cook the egg.</p>
<h3>Peanut butter</h3>
<ul>
<li>Spread peanut butter on sandwiches, desserts or hot breakfasts. </li>
<li>Swirl peanut butter into soft ice cream or yogurt. </li>
<li>Use peanut butter as a dip for raw vegetables or fruit slices. </li>
</ul>
<h3>Nuts and seeds (only for children over four years old)</h3>
<ul>
<li>Serve nuts or seeds as snacks. </li>
<li>Add chopped or ground nuts to breakfast foods, salads or desserts. </li>
<li>Try rolling a banana in chopped nuts. </li>
</ul>
